## Why This Is Asked\n\nTests understanding of inter-thread synchronization without kernel primitives, and memory ordering.\\n\n## Key Concepts\n- Atomic operations, memory_order semantics\\n- Barrier synchronization, generation counters\\n- Spin-wait considerations and pause\n\n## Code Example\n```c
typedef struct {
  atomic_int count;
  atomic_uint64_t gen;
  int N;
} barrier_t;

void barrier_enter(barrier_t* b, int id) {
  uint64_t g = atomic_load_explicit(&b->gen, memory_order_relaxed);
  if (atomic_fetch_add_explicit(&b->count, 1, memory_order_acq_rel) == b->N - 1) {
    atomic_store_explicit(&b->count, 0, memory_order_relaxed);
    atomic_fetch_add_explicit(&b->gen, 1, memory_order_release);
  } else {
    while (atomic_load_explicit(&b->gen, memory_order_acquire) == g) {
      _mm_pause();
    }
  }
}
```
\n## Follow-up Questions\n- How would you ensure fairness if threads stall? \n- How would you extend for multiple, consecutive barrier phases?\n

## Why This Is Asked
Evaluates understanding of locality-aware, lock-free data structure design and memory reclamation strategies under multi-core contention scenarios.

## Key Concepts
- Two-tier queue architecture with per-core local buffers
- ABA problem prevention using per-slot sequence counters
- Memory reclamation via epoch-based reclamation or hazard pointers
- Cache-line alignment optimization to minimize false sharing
- Progress guarantees and fairness under high contention

## Code Example
```c
// Prototypes
typedef struct { unsigned long long seq; void *ptr; } slot_t;
typedef struct {
    slot_t *slots;
    atomic_uint_fast64_t head;
    atomic_uint_fast64_t tail;
    size_t capacity;
    char padding[64 - sizeof(atomic_uint_fast64_t) * 2 - sizeof(void*) - sizeof(size_t)];
} ring_buffer_t;

// Local ring operations
bool local_enqueue(ring_buffer_t *local, ring_buffer_t *global, void *item);
bool local_dequeue(ring_buffer_t *local, void **item);

// Global ring operations
bool global_enqueue(ring_buffer_t *global, void *item);
bool global_dequeue(ring_buffer_t *global, void **item);

// Batch drain from local to global
void drain_local_to_global(ring_buffer_t *local, ring_buffer_t *global);
```

## Item Flow
1. **Fast Path**: Core enqueues to its local ring buffer using simple atomic operations
2. **Transfer**: When local buffer is full/empty or during periodic draining, batch transfers occur to/from global ring
3. **Cross-Core**: Threads from different cores interact only through the global ring

## ABA Prevention
Per-slot sequence counters increment on each write, combined with slot indices to create unique identifiers that prevent ABA during compare-and-swap operations.

## Memory Reclamation
Implement epoch-based reclamation where threads enter epochs before accessing shared data, ensuring safe retirement of nodes once all threads have advanced past the epoch where nodes were unlinked.

## Progress Guarantees
- Local operations: Wait-free (bounded by local buffer size)
- Global operations: Lock-free with exponential backoff under contention
- Fairness: Priority inheritance through drain scheduling

## Microbenchmark Plan
1. **Single-Core**: Measure local operation throughput
2. **Multi-Core**: Test with varying producer/consumer ratios
3. **Contention**: Measure performance under high concurrent access
4. **Latency**: Track operation tail latency distribution
5. **Comparison**: Benchmark against single-tier lock-free queue

