## Why This Is Asked
Tests basic concurrent data structure design and practical use of atomics and memory ordering in a beginner-friendly but realistic setting.

## Key Concepts
- MPSC synchronization using a shared tail and a local consumer head
- Atomic fetch_add for slot reservation
- Memory ordering: release on enqueue, acquire on dequeue
- Correct wrap-around handling in a fixed-size buffer

## Code Example
```javascript
// Pseudo-C code (C11 atomics style)
#define N (1<<12)
typedef struct { uint64_t data; uint64_t seq; } slot_t;
slot_t buf[N];
atomic_uintptr_t tail = 0; // producer index
size_t head = 0; // consumer index

bool enqueue(uint64_t v){
  size_t t = atomic_fetch_add_explicit(&tail, 1, memory_order_relaxed);
  if (t >= N) return false;
  buf[t].data = v;
  atomic_thread_fence(memory_order_release);
  buf[t].seq = t; // simple wrap-safe signal
  return true;
}

bool dequeue(uint64_t* out){
  if (head >= atomic_load_explicit(&tail, memory_order_acquire)) return false;
  *out = buf[head].data;
  head++;
  return true;
}
```

## Follow-up Questions
- How would you extend this to detect and recover from corrupted data?
- How would you benchmark throughput under 1000 producers vs 1 consumer?

## Why This Is Asked
Tests understanding of memory hierarchy and data locality by forcing cache-friendly tiling in a simple kernel.

## Key Concepts
- Tile size vs cache capacity; 2D blocking; stride-1 vs stride-N access patterns; bounds handling.
- Prefetching to hide memory latency; ensure no aliasing via separate buffers.

## Code Example
```c
void transpose_tiled(const float* A, float* B, int N) {
  const int Bsz = 32;
  for (int br = 0; br < N; br += Bsz) {
    for (int bc = 0; bc < N; bc += Bsz) {
      for (int i = 0; i < Bsz; ++i) {
        int r = br + i;
        if (r >= N) break;
        for (int j = 0; j < Bsz; ++j) {
          int c = bc + j;
          if (c >= N) break;
          B[c * N + r] = A[r * N + c];
        }
      }
    }
  }
}
```

## Follow-up Questions
- How to handle N not divisible by 32; impact on correctness and performance?
- How would you adapt to double precision or non-square matrices?
- Would you vectorize with AVX/NEON and what changes? How to measure speedup?

## Why This Is Asked
