A lock-free, bounded task queue with work-stealing for a 2-socket x86-64 server. Each worker maintains a private deque with local push and shared steal endpoints. Producers push to their local queue; if full, they fallback to a shared ring buffer. Workers first attempt fast local pop, then steal from peer deques, and finally poll the shared ring. Per-slot sequence counters prevent ABA problems, and proper memory fences ensure visibility across threads.

## API Prototypes

```c
typedef struct {
    void* task;
    uint64_t seq;
} TaskSlot;

typedef struct {
    TaskSlot* slots;
    uint64_t mask;
    _Atomic uint64_t bottom;
    _Atomic uint64_t top;  // shared for stealing
} LocalDeque;

int push(LocalDeque* q, void* task);
void* pop(LocalDeque* q);
void* steal(LocalDeque* q);
void* shared_ring_pop(SharedRing* ring);
```

## Pseudo-code

**push(q, task):**
```
bottom = fetch_add(&q->bottom, 1, relaxed);
if (bottom - q->top > q->mask) 
    return FULL;  // fallback to shared ring
slot = &q->slots[bottom & q->mask];
while (slot->seq != bottom) pause();  // wait for slot
slot->task = task;
store_fence();
slot->seq = bottom + 1;
return SUCCESS;
```

**pop(q):**
```
bottom = load(&q->bottom, relaxed) - 1;
store(&q->bottom, bottom, relaxed);
fence();
top = load(&q->top, relaxed);
if (bottom >= top) 
    return empty local, try steal;
slot = &q->slots[bottom & q->mask];
task = slot->task;
if (load(&slot->seq, acquire) != bottom + 1) 
    return CAS失败, try steal;  // stolen
CAS(&q->bottom, bottom, top);  // retry if needed
return task;
```

**steal(q):**
```
top = fetch_add(&q->top, 1, acquire);
fence();
bottom = load(&q->bottom, acquire);
if (top >= bottom) return EMPTY;
slot = &q->slots[top & q->mask];
while (slot->seq != top) pause();
task = slot->task;
slot->seq = top + 1;
return task;
```

## Microbenchmark

**Light contention:** 1 producer, 1 consumer per core, 10K tasks.

**Heavy contention:** 4 producers, 4 consumers per core, 1M tasks.

**Metrics:**
- Push/pop latency (p50, p99, max)
- Throughput (tasks/sec)
- Cache miss rate per operation
- Cross-NUMA socket traffic

**Methodology:**
1. Warm-up phase (100K tasks)
2. Measure phase (1M tasks)
3. Vary contention by adjusting producer/consumer ratios
4. Compare with baseline (single-threaded, lock-based)

