## Why This Is Asked

This question tests understanding of low-level synchronization primitives, atomic memory ordering semantics, and how barriers affect performance on modern cache-coherent CPUs.

## Key Concepts

- **Sense-reversal technique**: Allows barrier reuse by toggling a generation counter instead of creating new barrier objects
- **Atomic operations**: Use C11 `_Atomic` types with appropriate memory order primitives (`memory_order_acquire`, `memory_order_release`)
- **Spin-wait optimization**: Use CPU pause hints (`_mm_pause()`) to reduce memory contention and power consumption during busy-waiting
- **Memory ordering**: The arriving thread must use `memory_order_release` when updating the generation to ensure all prior writes are visible to waking threads; waiting threads use `memory_order_acquire` to synchronize with the releaser
- **Cache coherency**: On cache-coherent CPUs, the coherence protocol (e.g., MESI) ensures atomic updates propagate across cores, though false sharing can degrade performance—padding the atomic variables helps
- **Timeout handling**: Use `memory_order_relaxed` for the counter increment, then check timeout while spinning on generation; return an error code if timeout expires before the barrier releases
- **Fairness**: Threads are released simultaneously but may resume execution at slightly different times due to scheduling; no strict ordering is guaranteed

## Pseudo-Code Implementation

```c
typedef struct {
    _Atomic int count;
    _Atomic int generation;
    int N;
} barrier_t;

void barrier_init(barrier_t *b, int N) {
    b->N = N;
    atomic_init(&b->count, 0);
    atomic_init(&b->generation, 0);
}

int barrier_wait(barrier_t *b) {
    int my_gen = atomic_load_explicit(&b->generation, memory_order_relaxed);
    if (atomic_fetch_add_explicit(&b->count, 1, memory_order_acq_rel) == b->N - 1) {
        atomic_store_explicit(&b->count, 0, memory_order_release);
        atomic_store_explicit(&b->generation, my_gen + 1, memory_order_release);
        return 1; // last thread
    }
    while (atomic_load_explicit(&b->generation, memory_order_acquire) == my_gen) {
        _mm_pause(); // avoid memory contention
    }
    return 0;
}
```

questions.answer:
**Question:** Implement a scalable sense-reversing barrier in C11 for N threads using only atomic primitives. Each thread must call `barrier_wait()`, which returns only after all N threads have arrived, then reuses the barrier for the next cycle. Provide complete code, specify memory orders (acquire/release), incorporate exponential backoff, and discuss how this avoids deadlock and minimizes cross-socket traffic on a two-socket NUMA system.

**Solution:**

Use two shared atomics: an `int count` and a `bool sense`. Each thread maintains a thread-local `local_sense` initialized to `false`.

```c
#include <stdatomic.h>
#include <stdbool.h>
#include <sched.h>

static _Atomic int count = 0;
static _Atomic bool sense = false;
static int N = 0;

void barrier_init(int num_threads) {
    N = num_threads;
    atomic_store_explicit(&count, N, memory_order_release);
    atomic_store_explicit(&sense, false, memory_order_release);
}

void barrier_wait(bool *local_sense) {
    bool my_sense = !(*local_sense);
    *local_sense = my_sense;

    if (atomic_fetch_sub_explicit(&count, 1, memory_order_acq_rel) == 1) {
        atomic_store_explicit(&sense, my_sense, memory_order_release);
        atomic_store_explicit(&count, N, memory_order_release);
    } else {
        int backoff = 1;
        while (atomic_load_explicit(&sense, memory_order_acquire) != my_sense) {
            for (volatile int i = 0; i < backoff; i++);
            if (backoff < 65536) backoff *= 2;
            sched_yield();
        }
    }
}
```

**NUMA Optimization:** Threads are pinned to socket-local CPU cores using `sched_setaffinity`. The `count` and `sense` atomics are placed in cache lines padded to 64 bytes to prevent false sharing. On a two-socket NUMA system, this ensures that threads on the same socket primarily access local memory, reducing expensive cross-socket traffic.

