## Why This Is Asked
This question assesses the candidate's understanding of lightweight synchronization primitives, cache coherency effects, and memory ordering in concurrent programming.

## Key Concepts
- **Sense-reversing barrier**: A centralized synchronization mechanism where threads signal arrival by setting a flag, and the last thread flips a generation counter to release waiters
- **False sharing prevention**: Padding each thread's slot to 64 bytes (cache line size) ensures threads do not contend on the same cache line
- **Memory ordering**: Use relaxed ordering for per-thread arrival flags, and acquire/release semantics for the generation counter to ensure proper synchronization

## Code Example
```c
// Pseudo-code for a cache-friendly, lock-free barrier
typedef struct { alignas(64) volatile int ready; } slot_t;

slot_t slots[N];
volatile int generation = 0;

void barrier_enter(int tid) {
    slots[tid].ready = 1;  // Signal arrival with relaxed memory order
    int gen = generation;  // Read current generation

    // Spin until all threads arrive and generation changes
    while (generation == gen) { /* spin */ }
}

void barrier_wait(int tid) {
    // Check if this is the last arriving thread
    int arrived = 0;
    for (int i = 0; i < N; i++) {
        arrived += slots[i].ready;
    }

    if (arrived == N) {
        // Last thread: flip generation and reset slots
        for (int i = 0; i < N; i++) slots[i].ready = 0;
        generation++;
    }
}
```

