## Why This Question Is Asked

This question assesses the ability to design a low-latency, cache-friendly memory allocator with cross-thread reclamation. It evaluates understanding of ABA avoidance, per-size caches, and NUMA implications on modern multi-socket systems.

## Key Concepts

- **Lock-free, per-size-class slab allocator** with thread-local caches to minimize synchronization overhead
- **Cross-thread transfer** via a global lock-free pool enabling efficient memory sharing between threads
- **ABA avoidance** using pointer tagging (e.g., utilizing low bits as a collision counter)
- **Epoch-based reclamation** versus hazard pointers for safe memory reuse
- **Cache-line alignment** to prevent false sharing and control fragmentation

## Code Example

```c
typedef struct {
    void *next;           // Free list pointer
    uintptr_t tag;        // ABA prevention counter
} slab_object_t;

typedef struct {
    void *slabs;          // Pointer to slab pages
    _Atomic(slab_object_t *) free_list[4];  // Per-size free lists
    _Atomic(uintptr_t) tag;                // Global ABA tag
} thread_cache_t;

typedef struct {
    void *slab;
    size_t size_class;
    _Atomic(struct global_pool *) next;
} global_pool_t;

// Thread-local cache declaration
thread_local thread_cache_t tls_cache;

// Allocation API
void *slab_alloc(size_t size) {
    int idx = get_size_class_index(size);
    slab_object_t *obj = atomic_load(&tls_cache.free_list[idx], memory_order_acquire);

    while (obj) {
        slab_object_t *next = obj->next;
        uintptr_t expected_tag = obj->tag;

        if (atomic_compare_exchange_weak(&tls_cache.free_list[idx], &next,
            (slab_object_t *)((uintptr_t)obj->next | ((expected_tag + 1) << 2)),
            memory_order_release, memory_order_relaxed)) {
            return obj;
        }
    }

    // Cache miss: fetch from global pool
    return fetch_from_global_pool(idx);
}

// Free API
void slab_free(void *ptr, size_t size) {
    int idx = get_size_class_index(size);
    slab_object_t *obj = (slab_object_t *)ptr;
    obj->tag = atomic_fetch_add(&tls_cache.tag, 1) + 1;

    do {
        obj->next = tls_cache.free_list[idx];
    } while (!atomic_compare_exchange_weak(&tls_cache.free_list[idx], &obj->next,
        obj, memory_order_release, memory_order_relaxed));
}

// Epoch-based reclamation (pseudocode)
void epoch_reclaim(slab_object_t *obj) {
    atomic_fetch_add(&current_epoch, 1);
    if (atomic_load(&retired_count) > THRESHOLD) {
        // Safely free objects from previous epoch
        sweep_retired_objects();
    }
}
```

## Performance Considerations

### Fragmentation
- Internal fragmentation is bounded by the per-size-class design (worst case: ~50% for objects slightly larger than half the slab size)
- External fragmentation remains minimal since slabs are fixed-size and预先 allocated

### Cache Alignment
- Align each object to cache line size (64 bytes) or use padding to eliminate false sharing between threads
- Global pool structures should occupy separate cache lines from thread-local data

### NUMA Awareness
- On a 2-socket x86-64 system, each socket should maintain a local slab pool
- Affinitize threads to sockets using `sched_setaffinity()` or platform-specific NUMA APIs
- Prefetch memory from the local NUMA node to minimize cross-socket memory access latency

