Design a PMEM ring buffer with N fixed-size slots stored in persistent memory. Each slot contains a sequence counter and payload. Head and tail pointers are stored in DRAM with periodic durable checkpoints to persistent memory.

**Data Layout:**
```
struct Slot {
    uint64_t seq;        // Sequence number
    char payload[];      // Variable-length data
}

struct Queue {
    Slot slots[N];       // PMEM region
    _Atomic uint64_t tail;   // DRAM (checkpointed)
    _Atomic uint64_t head;   // DRAM (checkpointed)
}
```

**Enqueue (Producer):**
```c
void enqueue(Queue* q, void* data, size_t len) {
    uint64_t tail = atomic_fetch_add(&q->tail, 1);
    Slot* slot = &q->slots[tail % N];

    // Wait for slot to be free
    while (slot->seq != tail) {}

    // Write payload and sequence
    memcpy(slot->payload, data, len);
    slot->seq = tail + 1;

    // Persist: flush cache line, fence
    clflushopt(slot);
    sfence();
}
```

**Dequeue (Consumer):**
```c
void* dequeue(Queue* q) {
    uint64_t head = q->head;
    Slot* slot = &q->slots[head % N];

    // Check if slot is ready
    if (slot->seq != head + 1) return NULL;

    // Invalidate and consume
    clflushopt(slot);  // ensure fresh read
    void* data = slot->payload;
    slot->seq = 0;  // mark empty

    atomic_store(&q->head, head + 1);
    checkpoint_head(q->head);
    return data;
}
```

**Recovery Plan:**
1. On restart, scan slots from head to tail
2. Find highest sequence number matching expected order
3. Reconstruct head pointer from committed slots
4. Resume processing from recovered position

