## Why This Is Asked
This question tests understanding of memory hierarchy and cache effects, which are crucial for writing high-performance, low-latency code in systems programming.

## Key Concepts
- **False sharing**: When two threads modify variables that share the same cache line, even if they access different variables, the cache coherence protocol forces invalidation and reloads
- **Cache lines**: Typically 64 bytes on modern CPUs; data is transferred between main memory and CPU caches in these blocks
- **MESI protocol**: Cache coherence protocol (Modified, Exclusive, Shared, Invalid) that ensures consistency but introduces overhead when false sharing occurs
- **Memory alignment and padding**: Restructuring data to occupy separate cache lines eliminates false sharing at the cost of increased memory usage
- **pthreads and barriers**: Lightweight threading with synchronization primitives to coordinate threads and measure timing accurately

