## Why This Is Asked

Tests understanding of lock-free free-lists, memory safety, and practical memory management in low-level code. It also checks defensive programming (double-free) and how to reason about under-concurrency correctness.

## Key Concepts

- Lock-free free-list stored inside blocks; head is an atomic pointer; push/pop via CAS loops
- Alignment and pool boundaries; membership checks to detect invalid frees
- Avoids dynamic allocations; upfront memory footprint predictable
- Stress testing under contention and memory ordering effects

## Code Example

```javascript
// Pseudo-C-like representation
typedef struct Block {
  struct Block* next;
  char payload[SIZE];
} Block;
Block pool[N];
_A< Block* > head;

Block* allocate() {
  Block* old = atomic_load(&head);
  while (old) {
    Block* next = old->next;
    if (atomic_compare_exchange_weak(&head, &old, next))
      return old;
    old = atomic_load(&head);
  }
  return NULL;
}

void free(Block* b) {
  Block* old = atomic_load(&head);
  do {
    b->next = old;
  } while (!atomic_compare_exchange_weak(&head, &old, b));
}
```

